GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 909
Short Title: State Infrastructure Bank Board. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Reives, Bell, Howard, and Ross (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Commerce and Economic Development, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and
Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH A STATE INFRASTRUCTURE BANK BOARD.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1. Article 10 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes is amended by
5 adding a new Part to read:
6 "Part 23. State Infrastructure Bank Board.
7 "§ 143B-472.130. Establishment of State Infrastructure Bank Board.
8 (a) Establishment. – There is established a State Infrastructure Bank Board. The Board
9 shall be located in the Department of Commerce for administrative purposes only and shall
10 function independently of the Department. The Board shall establish, administer, and receive
11 federal funds for a State infrastructure bank authorized by the Intermodal Surface Transportation
12 Efficiency Act of 1991, Public Law 102-240, as amended, the National Highway System
13 Designation Act of 1995, Public Law 104-59, as amended, and any other federal law authorizing
14 and governing the use of federal funds for a transportation infrastructure banking program.
15 Through the State infrastructure bank, the Board may also administer and receive State funds and
16 private funds for transportation projects, water and sewer projects, and other infrastructure
17 projects.
18 (b) Federal Financial Assistance. – The Board may apply for, receive, and administer
19 federal financial assistance necessary to fund the State infrastructure bank. The Board shall
20 comply with all conditions and requirements related to the federal financial assistance.
21 (c) Use of Funds. – Except as otherwise prohibited under federal law, the Board may
22 utilize the following funds for the purpose of providing loans or other financial assistance to
23 governmental units, including toll authorities:
24 (1) Federal funds, State funds, and private funds to finance the costs of
25 transportation projects, including aviation projects.
26 (2) State funds and private funds to finance the costs of water and sewer projects
27 and other infrastructure projects.
28 (d) Conditions and Repayment. – Loans or other financial assistance provided under this
29 section are subject to repayment and conditioned upon the establishment of any security and the
30 payment of any fees and interest rates deemed necessary by the Board. Governmental units may
31 apply for loans and execute debt instruments payable to the State in order to obtain loans or other
32 financial assistance provided for in this section. The Board shall require that applicants pledge
33 as security for the obligations revenues derived from operation of the benefited facilities or
34 systems, other sources of revenue, or their faith and credit, or any combination thereof. The faith
*H909-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 and credit of the governmental units shall not be pledged or be deemed to have been pledged
2 unless the requirements of Article 4 of Chapter 159 of the General Statutes have been met. The
3 Board may apply a municipality's share of funds allocated under G.S. 136-41.1 or G.S. 136-44.20
4 as necessary to ensure repayment of funds advanced under this section.
5 (e) Account; Nonreversion of Funds. – The Board shall establish jointly with the State
6 Treasurer one or more separate infrastructure banking accounts with necessary fiscal controls
7 and accounting procedures. Federal funds for funds credited to this account shall not revert, and
8 interest and other investment income shall accrue to the account and may be used to provide
9 loans and other financial assistance as provided under this section.
10 (f) Rules. – The Board may establish rules necessary to establish and administer the State
11 infrastructure bank.
12 (g) Effect on Transportation Investment Strategy Formula. – The Board shall not modify
13 the formula for the distribution of funds established by G.S. 136-189.11.
14 (h) Cooperation on Water and Sewer Projects. – With respect to water and sewer projects,
15 the Board shall cooperate with the Division of Water Infrastructure of the Department of
16 Environmental Quality and the State Water Infrastructure Authority established under Article 5
17 of Chapter 159G of the General Statutes.
18 (i) Debt Instruments. – The State Treasurer, with the assistance of the Local Government
19 Commission, shall develop and adopt appropriate debt instruments for use under this section.
20 The Local Government Commission shall develop and adopt appropriate procedures for the
21 delivery of debt instruments to the State without any public bidding.
22 (j) Review and Approval of Loans. – The Board shall review and approve all proposed
23 loans and other financial assistance to applicants under this section. In addition, the Local
24 Government Commission shall review and approve proposed loans to applicants under this
25 section pursuant to Articles 4 and 5 of Chapter 159 of the General Statutes, as if the issuance of
26 bonds was proposed, so far as those provisions are applicable.
27 (k) Outstanding Debt. – Loans authorized by this section are outstanding debt for the
28 purpose of Article 10 of Chapter 159 of the General Statutes.
29 "§ 143B-472.131. Membership of State Infrastructure Bank Board; meetings.
30 (a) Members. – The State Infrastructure Bank Board shall consist of the following voting
31 members:
32 (1) The Secretary of Commerce.
33 (2) The Secretary of Transportation.
34 (3) The Secretary of Environmental Quality.
35 (4) The State Treasurer.
36 (5) The State Auditor.
37 (6) The State Budget Officer.
38 (b) Terms. – The Board members shall serve terms coinciding with their respective
39 offices.
40 (c) Officers. – The Board shall elect from its members a chair and vice-chair of the Board.
41 (d) Meetings. – The Board shall meet on the call of the chair or any two members but
42 shall meet at least once every six months. Each member may be represented by a designee, who
43 shall have the same voting powers as the member. The Board shall meet in offices provided by
44 the Department of Commerce. In addition, the Department of Commerce shall provide the
45 necessary staff and supplies to help the Board accomplish its objectives. The Department of
46 Transportation, Department of Environmental Quality, and the Department of the State Treasurer
47 may also provide staff assistance.
48 (e) Rules. – The Board shall adopt rules, consistent with the requirements of this Part, for
49 reviewing and approving loans or other financial assistance provided under this Part. The Board
50 shall publish the rules on the Board's website or, if the Board does not have its own website, on
51 the Department of Commerce's website.
Page 2 House Bill 909-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (f) Quorum. – A quorum of the Board consists of a majority of the Board's total
2 membership.
3 (g) Reports. – The Board shall report on its activities quarterly to the Joint Legislative
4 Commission on Governmental Operations.
5 (h) Compensation. – Members shall serve without compensation but may receive travel
6 and subsistence in accordance with G.S. 138-6."
7 SECTION 2. G.S. 136-18(12a) is repealed.
8 SECTION 3. G.S. 147-69.2 reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 147-69.2. Investments authorized for special funds held by State Treasurer.
10 (a) This section applies to funds held by the State Treasurer to the credit of each of the
11 following:
12 …
13 (25) Funds held by the State infrastructure bank established under
14 G.S. 143B-472.130.
15 …."
16 SECTION 4. The State infrastructure bank, established in G.S. 136-18(12a),
17 including all funds held by it, are transferred to the State Infrastructure Bank Board, established
18 in G.S. 143B-472.130, as enacted by Section 1 of this act.
19 SECTION 5. Section 1 of this act becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
20 loans and other financial assistance applied for on or after that date. The remainder of this act
21 becomes effective July 1, 2025.
